      "name": "Primary stiffness QoI comparison — non-cannulated construct",
      "description": "FEA-predicted construct stiffness (mean 187.4 N/mm, 95% PI 174.2–200.6 N/mm) is assessed against the experimental distribution from the Nagaraja et al. bench dataset. The normalized error metric E/uval was computed as 1.31, falling below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96, indicating satisfactory agreement. The assessment team notes that the Rohlmann et al. (2001) rigid-block ASTM F1717 dataset, which employs machined aluminum vertebral body surrogates, was reviewed during protocol development and found to provide strong corroborating evidence for the stiffness QoI. Agreement between the FEA ensemble and the Rohlmann rigid-block data is described as excellent (mean percent difference 3.8%), lending additional confidence to the modeling framework. No sensitivity analysis was performed to isolate the effect of surrogate compliance on predicted stiffness, as both datasets nominally conform to ASTM F1717 boundary conditions. The validation is judged to meet the acceptance criterion."
